---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Articles & Buyer Guides | Sonoma Lawyers Realty"
  description="Articles, guides, and legal insights for Sonoma County real estate buyers. Written by Dean L. Johnson, Attorney & Real Estate Broker at Sonoma Lawyers Realty."
>
  <section style="margin-top: 120px; padding-bottom: 6rem;">
    <h1 class="section-title">Articles</h1>
    <p class="section-subtitle" style="max-width: 100%;">Legal insights and practical guides for Sonoma County real estate buyers, written by an attorney who is also your broker.</p>

    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 3rem auto; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2.5rem;">

      <!-- Article Card: Buyer-Broker Agreement (BRBC) -->
      <article style="background: var(--white); border-radius: 4px; box-shadow: 0 4px 30px var(--shadow); overflow: hidden; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);">
        <div style="padding: 2.5rem;">
          <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 1px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Buyer Representation &amp; Agreements</p>
          <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 1.3;">
            <a href="/media/buyer-broker-agreement-brbc-sonoma-county/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.2s;">
              The Dangerous Provisions in Buyer-Broker Agreements
            </a>
          </h2>
          <p style="color: var(--text-light); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            The standard California buyer-broker agreement (Form BRBC) was drafted to protect brokers, not buyers. Learn the five critical modifications every Sonoma County buyer must make before signing — and why the NAR settlement makes this more urgent than ever.
          </p>
          <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 2rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <a href="/media/buyer-broker-agreement-brbc-sonoma-county/" class="cta-button" style="display: inline-block; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              Read Article
            </a>
            <span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-light);">By Dean L. Johnson, Attorney &amp; Real Estate Broker</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Article Card: PTRA Well Ordinance -->
      <article style="background: var(--white); border-radius: 4px; box-shadow: 0 4px 30px var(--shadow); overflow: hidden; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);">
        <div style="padding: 2.5rem;">
          <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 1px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Rural Land &amp; Agricultural Property</p>
          <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 1.3;">
            <a href="/media/ptra-well-ordinance-sonoma-county-buyers/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.2s;">
              PTRA Well Ordinance: What Sonoma County Land Buyers Must Know
            </a>
          </h2>
          <p style="color: var(--text-light); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            If you're buying rural land, a vineyard, or agricultural property in Sonoma County, there's a local ordinance most buyers — and even many agents — don't fully understand until it's too late. The Public Trust Review Area (PTRA) can be the difference between a productive property and one with severely constrained water rights.
          </p>
          <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 2rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <a href="/media/ptra-well-ordinance-sonoma-county-buyers/" class="cta-button" style="display: inline-block; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              Read Article
            </a>
            <span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-light);">By Dean L. Johnson, Attorney &amp; Real Estate Broker</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Article Card: California Double Step-Up in Basis -->
      <article style="background: var(--white); border-radius: 4px; box-shadow: 0 4px 30px var(--shadow); overflow: hidden; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);">
        <div style="padding: 2.5rem;">
          <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 1px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Estate Planning &amp; Tax Strategy</p>
          <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 1.3;">
            <a href="/media/california-double-step-up-in-basis-sonoma-county/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.2s;">
              The California Double Step-Up in Basis: What Every Sonoma County Home Buyer Needs to Know Before They Close
            </a>
          </h2>
          <p style="color: var(--text-light); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            California's community property laws give married couples a powerful tax advantage that buyers in most other states don't have — the Double Step-Up in Basis. Understanding it before you close could save your family hundreds of thousands of dollars. Most buyers learn about it too late.
          </p>
          <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 2rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <a href="/media/california-double-step-up-in-basis-sonoma-county/" class="cta-button" style="display: inline-block; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; font-size: 0.9rem;">
              Read Article
            </a>
            <span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-light);">By Dean L. Johnson, Attorney &amp; Real Estate Broker</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
